{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7c1d9cf0-284d-4c8c-807c-0f608632e020","content":"Here are the **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (line 13 of `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via `System.IO.File` during evaluation is expensive — it forces synchronous disk I/O on every evaluation pass. Move this to a target that runs at build time instead.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the entire directory tree on every evaluation. If `node_modules`, `.git`, or other large directories exist, this becomes very slow. Use `DefaultItemExcludes` or narrow the pattern.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach nested import adds evaluation overhead. While 3 levels is moderate, this pattern can grow quickly. Consider flattening or consolidating imports.\n\n**Highest impact fix:** Remove the `File::ReadAllText` call — it's the most costly per-evaluation operation here.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f12dd6cf-f294-44e0-afb3-b804363de371","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a full picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues:\n\n1. **Deep import chain** (level1.props → level2.props → level3.props) - 3 levels deep\n2. **Expensive glob pattern** - `**\\*.*` which walks the entire directory tree\n3. **File I/O property function** - `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` reads a file during evaluation\n\nLet me provide a concise analysis.","outputTokens":448,"requestId":"DBC8:23D333:A84EF34:B74251F:69FD3A22"},"id":"239fd111-9dd4-4a83-bcba-e790b74d74f7","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:19:40.092Z","parentId":"c36749d4-2f82-4325-a1de-b037a3beb399"}
